ume","Completion of meiotic division"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring epididymal maturation, sperm cells undergo several important changes. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased cytoplasmic volume\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur - in fact, the opposite happens. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of the acrosome\u003C/strong\u003E occurs much earlier during spermiogenesis in the seminiferous tubules. The \u003Cstrong\u003Edevelopment of the flagellum\u003C/strong\u003E also occurs during spermiogenesis before the sperm reaches the epididymis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduction in cytoplasmic volume\u003C/strong\u003E. Sperm cells shed excess cytoplasm during epididymal transit, which is crucial for gaining motility. \u003Cstrong\u003ECompletion of meiotic division\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the seminiferous tubules before the sperm enters the epididymis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther key changes during epididymal maturation include acquisition of forward motility, changes in surface proteins, and membrane remodelling that enables fertilising capacity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sperm maturation in the epididymis involves reduction in cytoplasm and acquisition of motility","The acrosome forms earlier during spermatogenesis in the seminiferous tubules","Epididymal maturation is essential for sperm to gain fertilising capacity"],"references":["O\u0027Donnell L, Nicholls PK, O\u0027Bryan MK, McLachlan RI, Stanton PG. Spermiation: The process of sperm release. Spermatogenesis. 2011 Jan;1(1):14-35. doi: 10.4161/spmg.1.1.14525. PMID: 21866274; PMCID: PMC3158646","Griswold MD. Spermatogenesis: The Commitment to Meiosis. Physiol Rev. 2016 Jan;96(1):1-17. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00013.2015. PMID: 26537427; PMCID: PMC4698398","Chu DS, Shakes DC. Spermatogenesis. Adv Exp Med Biol. 2013;757:171-203. doi: 10.1007/978-1-4614-4015-4_7. PMID: 22872478; PMCID: PMC9217098"]}